I like to think you are happy. I hope your dream of moving to London came true. I hope you told your boss about me, due to our shared nationality. I just hope you are happy. Much like me you are easily moody and depressed so I just hope you are smiling.

You were the only one I saw. And I miss you so much. I miss your blunt honesty, your dark humor, your dirty jokes whispered in my ear, your proud smile when you showed me off to your friends, your stunned look when I wore that dress once ans I miss your dimpled smile.

You played it well. The indifference was very believable. But jealousy told on you. I was with other guys, admiring them. You sat next to me and trash talked them, told me they were too young and foolish. I pretended to be offended because those were my friends.

I also remember our coffee dates. You smoking, me sipping black coffee. It was the first time I didnt mind someone smoking around me. I still remember your smirk when you said Ill be fucked if they find me here with you but hey I dont care, youre worth it.

Realising I was in love was a stab in the back because our days were running out and soon we would not be together. I developed the annoying habit of not being able to breathe properly unless I knew where you were. Always looking for you in crowd.

I think I made you happy. Once you announced you were in a bad mood when I sat down for breakfast. A warning to stay away. I ignored it. At the end of that meal you were smiling and joking around. The guy I loved had returned.

You were funny. Effortlessly. Your humor wasnt understood by everyone so my friends found you grumpy and boring. You never failed to make me laugh though. Our jokes got more personal and after a week we had private jokes, intimate glances and signature sentences.

It was a cloudy day, like most days are in England. I remember thinking you looked intimidating as hell. I vowed to stay away. I failed, obviously. But then you smiled at a joke someone else said and dimples popped out on your cheeks. It was the best surprise of my life.

I remember that summer perfectly. The first time we spoke, the first time you made me laugh, the first time you made me cry and the first time I realised I was in love with you (which coincidentally is the first time you made me cry)
